<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Hana Highway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Hana Highway</h2><p><i>Hawaii, USA · HI-360, Pā'ia to Hana, Maui</i></p><p><b>600 curves, 56 one-lane bridges, every shade of green. The road is the destination.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>58 km (36 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3 hrs without stops; full day with</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Year-round; rainy season Nov–Mar can flood the lower bridges</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Narrow one-lane bridges, locals trying to commute, flash floods in stream crossings, sketchy turnouts</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>167</td></tr></table><hr><p>Built 1926; you cross 56 one-lane bridges and at least 600 curves in 84 km. The road is the journey — don't try to make Hana and back in a day, and don't try to get there by lunch. Yield to oncoming traffic on bridges (the convention is the first car to the approach goes; just give a wave). Stop at every fruit stand. The road continues past Hana around the back of Haleakalā as the Pi'ilani Highway, which is rougher, sometimes closed, and completes a circumnavigation of east Maui. Most rental contracts forbid that section. Locals laugh.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Pā'ia</b> — Last fuel stop and a former hippie outpost turned upscale surf town. Mama's Fish House is the legendary lunch.</li><li><b>Ho'okipa Beach</b> — World windsurfing capital. Green sea turtles haul out on the eastern end most afternoons — keep 3 m back.</li><li><b>Twin Falls</b> — First major waterfall, easy 10-minute walk on private land. Modest fee at the food stand.</li><li><b>Garden of Eden Arboretum</b> — 26-acre tropical garden; the establishing aerial shot in Jurassic Park (1993) was filmed flying over here.</li><li><b>Ke'anae Peninsula</b> — Black-lava peninsula formed in 1790 by Haleakalā's last eruption. Aunty Sandy's Banana Bread is non-negotiable.</li><li><b>Wai'ānapanapa State Park</b> — Black sand beach, sea caves, lava arch, sea-pencil-urchin tide pools. Reservation required for non-residents.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
